data.content:
Your code **does not use `Thread.Abort`**, `Thread.Interrupt`, or catch `ThreadAbortException`. The APIs it does use — `Thread.Start()`, `Thread.Join()`, and `Thread.Sleep()` — work identically in .NET 8. No Thread.Abort migration is needed.

That said, the idiomatic .NET 8 approach would replace raw threads with `Parallel.ForEachAsync` or `Task.WhenAll`, gaining cooperative cancellation via `CancellationToken` for free:

```csharp
public async Task RunBatchAsync(List<WorkItem> items, CancellationToken ct = default)
{
    await Parallel.ForEachAsync(items, ct, async (item, token) =>
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
        await Task.CompletedTask;
    });
}
```

This gives you cancellation support without ever needing `Thread.Abort`.
